{{Campaignbox Croatian War of Independence}}
'''Operation Swath-10''' ({{lang-hr|Operacija Otkos-10}}) was a military offensive undertaken by the [[Croatian Army]] (''Hrvatska vojska'' <U+2013> HV) against the [[SAO Western Slavonia]] [[Territorial Defense Forces (Yugoslavia)|Territorial Defense Forces]] on the [[Bilogora]] Mountain, in the region of western [[Slavonia]]. The operation took place from 31 October till 4 November 1991 during the [[Croatian War of Independence]] and ended in a Croatian victory. The military success set the stage for follow-up advances by the Croatian forces on the [[Papuk]] Mountain in Operation Papuk-91 fought in late November and December. By the end of the year, the HV gained control of the entire Papuk, securing transport routes between eastern Slavonia and the rest of [[Croatia]].

The offensives were accompanied by displacement of nearly entire [[Croatian Serb]] population of the area captured by the HV. The refugees initially fled to [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], but most of them were soon settled in [[Yugoslav People's Army]]-held [[Baranja]] region in the east of Croatia. The event provoked accusations that the Croatian troops committed [[ethnic cleansing]] and abuses of [[civil rights]] in the offensive. The accusations were contradicted by a [[European Community Monitor Mission]] (ECMM) report made following an ECMM team tour of the area captured by the Croatian forces, two days after the offensive ended. During Operation Papuk-91, retreating [[White Eagles (paramilitary)|White Eagles]] paramilitaries committed the [[Vo<U+0107>in massacre]]. The [[war crime]]s committed in [[Vo<U+0107>in]] are prosecuted at the [[International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia]].

==Background==
{{main|1991 Yugoslav campaign in Croatia}}
Within the [[1991 Yugoslav campaign in Croatia]], the 5th ([[Banja Luka]]) Corps of the [[Yugoslav People's Army]] (''Jugoslovenska Narodna Armija'' <U+2013> JNA) was tasked with advancing north through western [[Slavonia]] region, from [[Oku<U+010D>ani]] to [[Daruvar]] and [[Virovitica]], and with a secondary drive from Oku<U+010D>ani towards [[Kutina]].<ref>{{harvnb|Marijan|2012b|p=262}}</ref> This task was essentially consistent with the line expected to be reached by the main thrust of the JNA advancing from the eastern Slavonia in about a week. The linkup was designed to facilitate a further advance west to [[Zagreb]] and [[Vara<U+017E>din]].<ref name=Marijan12b261>{{harvnb|Marijan|2012b|p=261}}</ref> The Corps had already deployed a [[Battlegroup (army)|battlegroup]] of the 265th Mechanised Brigade near Oku<U+010D>ani to support the advance that started on 21 September, and reached the [[Papuk]] Mountains. The corps received two motorised and one artillery brigades as reinforcements during the advance, but the problems with morale and desertions experienced by the JNA elsewhere were also present in the Banja Luka Corps.<ref name=Marijan12b266>{{harvnb|Marijan|2012b|p=266}}</ref>

The JNA was stopped by the [[Croatian National Guard]] (''Zbor Narodne Garde'' - ZNG) between [[Novska]], [[Nova Gradi<U+0161>ka]] and [[Pakrac]], even though [[SAO Western Slavonia]] [[Territorial Defense Forces (Yugoslavia)|Territorial Defense Forces]] (''Teritorijalna odbrana'' <U+2013> TO) units took positions on the [[Bilogora]] and Papuk north of Pakrac, near Virovitica and [[Slatina, Croatia|Slatina]] with no JNA support.<ref name=BB102>{{harvnb|CIA|2002|p=102}}</ref> Capture of [[Ivanovo Selo]], {{convert/spell |7|km|abbr=off}} east of [[Grubi<U+0161>no Polje]] and {{convert/spell |8|km|abbr=off}} north of Daruvar on 21 September marked the territorial peak of the TO-held area on the Bilogora. The village was recaptured by the ZNG the same day at a cost of 7 dead and 15 wounded.<ref name=Nazor144/>

On 1 October, the Banja Luka Corps initiated probing attacks in the region, presaging a major effort employing the bulk of the corps three days later. The advance established defensive positions just outside Novska and Nova Gradi<U+0161>ka.<ref name=Marijan12b269270>{{harvnb|Marijan|2012b|pp=269<U+2013>270}}</ref> On 6 October, Pakrac was briefly isolated when the JNA captured [[Batinjani, Bjelovar-Bilogora County|Batinjani]] {{convert/spell |4|km|abbr=off}} northwest of the town, interdicting the last road available for supply of Pakrac. The ZNG recaptured the village the same day and drove the JNA back {{convert/spell |6|km|abbr=off}}, but it sustained 22 killed in the action.<ref name=Nazor144>{{harvnb|Nazor|2007|p=144}}</ref> The JNA captured [[Jasenovac, Sisak-Moslavina County|Jasenovac]] on 8 October. [[Lipik]] and a part of Pakrac were captured four days later.<ref name=Marijan12b269270/> By that time the JNA offensive in western Slavonia had lost its momentum,<ref name=Marijan12a110>{{harvnb|Marijan|2012a|p=110}}</ref> and the ZNG made minor advances north of Novska and west of Nova Gradi<U+0161>ka on 13 and 16 October.<ref name=Nazor144/> The Croatian authorities considered that the war situation was no longer critical. This assessment was followed by an order to prepare and implement plans for a counter-offensive on 15 October.<ref>{{harvnb|Marijan|2012a|p=107}}</ref> On 29 October, the ZNG launched [[Operation Hurricane-91]] against positions held by the JNA and the TO near Novska and Nova Gradi<U+0161>ka.<ref>{{harvnb|Nazor|2007|p=134}}</ref>

==Order of battle==
The TO forces in the Bilogora Mountain region were formally a part of the 28th Partisan Division, commanded by [[Colonel]] Nikola Mari<U+0107>.<ref name=Skvorc119>{{harvnb|<U+0160>kvorc|2010|p=119}}</ref> In reality, the TO forces comprised approximately 1,750 soldiers provided with eight [[armoured vehicle]]s, ten cannons and twelve mortars.<ref name=Nazor138>{{harvnb|Nazor|2007|p=138}}</ref> The TO-force was organised in two battalions, headquartered in the villages of [[Mali Gr<U+0111>evac]] and Velika Peratovica, jointly commanded by Rade <U+010C>akmak<ref>{{harvnb|Ba<U+0161>i<U+0107>|Mi<U+0161>kulin|2010|p=470}}</ref> North of the TO-held area, the ZNG deployed the 127th Infantry Brigade in Virovitica area.<ref name="Basic485"/> In Grubi<U+0161>no Polje area, south of the Bilogora, the ZNG force was subordinated to the 57th Independent Battalion (later renamed the 77th Independent Battalion).<ref>{{harvnb|Ba<U+0161>i<U+0107>|Mi<U+0161>kulin|2010|p=476}}</ref> The attacking ZNG force, under command of Colonel Franjo Kova<U+010D>evi<U+0107>,<ref>{{harvnb|Ba<U+0161>i<U+0107>|Mi<U+0161>kulin|2010|p=483}}</ref> consisted of 2,647 troops, supported by twelve armoured vehicles, eighteen cannons and twenty {{convert|120|mm|adj=on}} mortars&mdash;surpassing the defending TO force in every aspect except for the [[close air support]] provided by the [[Yugoslav Air Force]] to the TO. The ZNG originally planned to deploy the 105th Infantry Brigade and "Omega" special police company from [[Bjelovar]], but the two units had to be committed elsewhere and were not available for the offensive.<ref name=Nazor138/>

