Operation Swath-10 was tasked with restoring the [[D5 road (Croatia)|Virovitica<U+2013>Lon<U+010D>arica<U+2013>Grubi<U+0161>no Polje road]] to Croatian control, cutting off and destroying the TO forces deployed in the area of the road&mdash;the northernmost part of the western Slavonia captured by the TO or the JNA. Furthermore, those objectives were also designed to deny the Banja Luka Corps support if it attempted to break through towards Virovitica, controlling the last remaining supply route between Zagreb and Slavonia, shorten Croatian defensive positions and improve morale of the troops and civilian population.<ref name=Nazor137>{{harvnb|Nazor|2007|p=137}}</ref> The offensive was originally scheduled for 15 October, but it was postponed for two weeks due to unavailability of the 105th Infantry Brigade and the special police. The operation plan expected the ZNG to cut off the two TO battalions on the Bilogora Mountain within two days of fighting, and the second stage of the offensive called for destruction of the trapped TO force.<ref name=Nazor1378>{{harvnb|Nazor|2007|pp=137<U+2013>138}}</ref> The operation was authorised by Colonel Miroslav Jezer<U+010D>i<U+0107>, commander of Bjelovar Operational Zone as early as 7 October.<ref name=Nazor136>{{harvnb|Nazor|2007|p=136}}</ref>

The offensive was launched at 6&nbsp;am on 31 October. A 50-minute [[Barrage (artillery)|artillery bombardment]] was followed by ZNG advance in three groups.<ref name=Nazor136/> The 57th Independent Battalion advanced from the south, the 127th Infantry Brigade from the north and the 1st Battalion of the 127th Infantry Brigade from the northwest.<ref name="Nazor130"/> The same day, the ZNG captured the villages of [[Velika Barna]], [[Gornja Kova<U+010D>ica]] and [[Zrinska]] northwest of Grubi<U+0161>no Polje<U+2013>[[Veliki Gr<U+0111>evac]] road. That also secured the Grubi<U+0161>no Polje The ZNG also advanced along the Virovitica<U+2013>Grubi<U+0161>no Polje road, arriving at the outskirts of Mala Peratovica, {{convert/spell |4|km|abbr=off}} east of Grubi<U+0161>no Polje, and approaching [[Lon<U+010D>arica]], {{convert/spell |11|km|abbr=off}} south of Virovitica.<ref name=Basic485>{{harvnb|Ba<U+0161>i<U+0107>|Mi<U+0161>kulin|2010|p=485}}</ref> The TO forces offered strong resistance, especially near Lon<U+010D>arica, even though the battlefield situation was described as hopeless. The TO requested Yugoslav Air Force to provide close air support,<ref name=Basic4856>{{harvnb|Ba<U+0161>i<U+0107>|Mi<U+0161>kulin|2010|pp=485<U+2013>486}}</ref> and between four and six aircraft were deployed in response.<ref name=Nazor138/>

On 1 November, the ZNG conducted mop-up in the areas northwest of Grubi<U+0161>no Polje. The next day, the TO force started to retreat towards the Papuk Mountain. Lon<U+010D>arica and Dap<U+010D>eva<U+010D>ki Br<U+0111>ani (another village situated approximately {{convert/spell |2|km|abbr=off}} northeast of Mala Peratovica along the Virovitica<U+2013>Grubi<U+0161>no Polje road) were captured by the Croatian force on 3 November, after they defeated strong TO resistance.<ref name=Basic485/> That day, the ZNG was renamed the [[Croatian Army]] (''Hrvatska vojska'' <U+2013> HV).<ref>{{harvnb|MORH}}</ref> After the two villages were captured, the HV forces advancing from Grubi<U+0161>no Polje and Virovitica linked up. The same day, the HV also captured the village of Velika Peratovica, isolated by the advances along the Virovitica<U+2013>Grubi<U+0161>no Polje road and the advance northwest of Grubi<U+0161>no Polje made on the first day of the offensive. On 4 November, the operation was declared completed after the HV secured the entire area.<ref name=Basic485/>

==Follow-up operations==
[[File:Map 4 - Croatia - Western Slavonia - September 1991 - January 1992.jpg|thumb|300px|Map showing the fighting in western Slavonia, September 1991&ndash;January 1992; Operation Swath-10 is depicted in the bulge (salient) near the top of the map; Operation Papuk-91, a follow-up to Operation Swath-10, is depicted in the central portion of the map]]

===Battle of Bastajski Br<U+0111>ani===
On 10 November, the 57th Independent Battalion advanced against the TO in the village of Veliki Miletinac, east of the area captured in Operation Swath-10, capturing the village the same day. Neighbouring Mali Miletinac was captured by the HV the next day. On 12 November, the HV captured the villages of Bastajski Br<U+0111>ani and Reki<U+0107>i. Two days later, the TO counterattacked and inflicted HV casualties of 9 dead and approximately 10 wounded, but the HV defence held. Another effort to recapture Bastajski Br<U+0111>ani was made by the TO, reinforced with 50 [[White Eagles (paramilitary)|White Eagles]] paramilitaries. The attack failed even though it was well prepared and supported by artillery because the defending HV force was alerted through [[signals intelligence]] and reinforced in anticipation of the attack. The White Eagles suffered 46 killed in the battle.<ref>{{harvnb|Nazor|2007|p=140}}</ref>

===Operation Papuk-91===
Operation Papuk-91 was devised as a follow-up of Operation Swath-10, involving advancing south from the Virovitica<U+2013>Osijek road, aimed at clearing the Papuk and the Psunj mountains, of the TO forces,<ref name=Nazor141/> elements of the 28th Partisan Division.<ref name=Skvorc119/> The offensive was approved by Jezer<U+010D>i<U+0107> at a meeting in Slatina on 23 November. The meeting was attended by HV [[Inspector General]] [[Martin <U+0160>pegelj]], Colonel Miljenko Crnjac (commanding officer of the 123rd Infantry Brigade), Colonel <U+0110>uro De<U+010D>ak (commanding officer of the 127th Infantry Brigade), Colonel Josip <U+010C>erni (commanding officer of the 136th Infantry Brigade) and commanders of other units tasked with supporting the offensive.<ref name=Nazor141>{{harvnb|Nazor|2007|p=141}}</ref>

The operation was launched on 28 November, and the HV advanced across a front spanning Grubi<U+0161>no Polje and [[Orahovica]] nearly {{convert|60|km|abbr=off}} further east.<ref name=Nazor141/> On 2 December, a detachment of the 123rd Infantry Brigade, en route to relieve troops manning a base on the Papuk, was ambushed and eleven soldiers were killed. On 10 December, the HV advanced onto the [[Psunj]] Mountain area north of Nova Gradi<U+0161>ka in an effort [[codename]]d Gradina, capturing the villages of <U+0160>njegavi<U+0107>, Sinlije, Golobrdac, Vu<U+010D>jak <U+010C>e<U+010D>avski, Ru<U+0161>evac, Jeminovac, <U+010C>e<U+010D>avac and Opr<U+0161>inac. The advance improved safety of the Nova Gradi<U+0161>ka<U+2013>[[Po<U+017E>ega, Croatia|Po<U+017E>ega]] road and secured the right flank of the Nova Gradi<U+0161>ka axis of the Operation Hurricane-91.<ref name=Nazor145>{{harvnb|Nazor|2007|p=145}}</ref>

On 12<U+2013>15 December, the HV captured a cluster of villages centered on [[<U+0110>ulovac]], southeast of the area captured in Operation Swath-10. The HV units approaching from the east captured [[Vo<U+0107>in]], approximately {{convert/spell |10|km|abbr=off}} southeast of <U+0110>ulovac, on 14<U+2013>15 December.<ref name=Nazor145/> Both Vo<U+0107>in and <U+0110>ulovac were badly damaged by the retreating TO and the White Eagles paramilitaries.<ref>{{harvnb|Duijzings|2000|pp=54<U+2013>55}}</ref> In addition, the retreating White Eagles killed [[Vo<U+0107>in massacre|43 civilians in Vo<U+0107>in]] on 13 December.<ref>{{harvnb|Duijzings|2000|p=55}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|ICTY|15 January 2003|p=6}}</ref> Bodies of the victims were mutilated and left unburied, presumably as a warning to others.<ref>{{harvnb|Gow|2003|p=163}}</ref>

On 16 December, the HV captured the villages of [[Gornji Vrhovci]], [[Kamenski Vu<U+010D>jak]] and Kamenski <U+0160>u<U+0161>njari situated approximately {{convert|15|km|abbr=off}} south of Vo<U+0107>in and {{convert|10|km|abbr=off}} west of [[Velika, Croatia]], restricting the TO forces to the southwest edge of the Papuk Mountain and the Psunj Mountain further south in operation codenamed Sokolina. The following day, the HV captured [[Novo Zve<U+010D>evo]] and a TO supply depot in the village, located halfway between Vo<U+0107>in and Kamenski Vu<U+010D>jak. The attack on Novo Zve<U+010D>evo was codenamed Johanesberg.<ref name=Nazor145/> On 18 December, the HV advanced southwest from Kamenski Vu<U+010D>jak (advance codenamed Lani<U+0161>ta), capturing the villages of [[Strije<U+017E>evica]], Bogda<U+0161>i<U+0107>, Amatovci and Kamenski <U+0160>eovci, arriving within {{convert/spell |1|km|abbr=off}} the village of Kamenska situated on the Pakrac<U+2013>Po<U+017E>ega road. The following three days the HV performed mopping up of the area.<ref name=Nazor146>{{harvnb|Nazor|2007|p=146}}</ref>

On 21 December, the HV launched a failed attack on Kamenska and the adjacent village of [[Mija<U+010D>i]] (codenamed Prkos). The TO withdrew from the area north of Kamenska, including the village of Sa<U+017E>ije on 24 December, and it retreated from Kamenska and Mija<U+010D>i the next day. The HV forces deployed in the area of Pakrac, west of the Papuk and the Psunj, advanced east to support the Operation Papuk-91, capturing the villages of [[Dereza, Po<U+017E>ega-Slavonia County|Dereza]], Gornji Grahovljani, Donji Grahovljani, [[Kusonje]] and [[<U+0160>panovica]] on 24<U+2013>25 December, leaving less than {{convert|15|km|abbr=off}} of the Pakrac<U+2013>Po<U+017E>ega road in between the HV units advancing from the west and the east.<ref name=Nazor146/> Operation Papuk-91 was concluded on 26 December, when the forces of the 123rd, the 127th and the 136th brigades linked up at [[Bu<U+010D>je, Pakrac|Bu<U+010D>je]]. The advance of the final day was codenamed Velebit.<ref>{{harvnb|Nazor|2007|pp=146<U+2013>147}}</ref>

==Aftermath==
In Operation Swath-10, the HV sustained loss of five dead.<ref>{{harvnb|Bjelovar.info|1 November 2011}}</ref> It captured {{convert|370|km2|abbr=off}} of western Slavonia containing 21 villages. While the HV met the objective of securing the Virovitica<U+2013>Grubi<U+0161>no Polje road it failed to trap the TO troops deployed to the area. This was later attributed to insufficient forces required to accomplish the goal, specifically unavailability of the 105th Infantry Brigade or possibly the 73rd Independent ([[Gare<U+0161>nica]]) Battalion. The two units were deployed in the area of Pakrac instead. The positions reached by the HV set the stage for further advance against the SAO Western Slavonia in Operation Papuk-91.<ref name=Nazor139>{{harvnb|Nazor|2007|p=139}}</ref> Some sources conflate Operations Swath-10 and Papuk-91, presenting the latter as a part of Operation Swath-10.<ref>{{harvnb|Thomas|Mikulan|2006|p=50}}</ref> Operation Papuk-91 completely eliminated threat to the road connecting the eastern Slavonia and Zagreb because the TO forces were pushed sufficiently far south, placing the road out of range of artillery.<ref>{{harvnb|<U+0160>tefan<U+010D>i<U+0107>|2011|p=428}}</ref> In Operation Papuk-19, the HV captured 110 settlements,<ref name=Nazor141/> as well as approximately {{convert|1230|km2|abbr=off}} of territory.<ref name=Nazor130>{{harvnb|Nazor|2007|p=130}}</ref>

In 2008, a monument to HV troops who took part in the offensive was unveiled in Grubi<U+0161>no Polje.<ref>{{harvnb|Virovitica.net|4 November 2008}}</ref> Another monument was erected on the Papuk Mountain to the 11 soldiers of the 123rd Infantry Brigade ambushed in Operation Papuk-91 on 2 December 1991.<ref>{{harvnb|034portal.hr|2 December 2011}}</ref> Operations Swath-10, Papuk-91, and Hurricane-91, executed in western Slavonia in late 1991, are considered to be the first Croatian offensive operations of liberation in the Croatian War of Independence.<ref>{{harvnb|MORH|2011|p=11}}</ref>

The [[International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia]] (ICTY) charged [[Vojislav <U+0160>e<U+0161>elj]] with a series of [[war crime]]s, including the killings committed by the White Eagles paramilitaries in Vo<U+0107>in on 13 December. The trial concluded in 2012, but the verdict is still pending {{as of|2013|July|lc=yes}}.<ref>{{harvnb|Jutarnji list|20 March 2012}}</ref> [[Slobodan Milo<U+0161>evi<U+0107>]], President of Serbia at the time of the killings, was also charged by the ICTY for the crimes committed in Vo<U+0107>in. Milo<U+0161>evi<U+0107> died before his trial at the ICTY was completed.<ref>{{harvnb|ICTY IT-02-54|p=1}}</ref>

===Refugees===
[[Croatian Serb]] civilian population fled the area affected by Operation Swath-10. According to Serbian sources, the population started to flee on the first day of the offensive, and by the second day approximately 800 vehicles left the region and crossed into [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]. The retreating columns included men of military age who refused to fight.<ref>{{harvnb|Ba<U+0161>i<U+0107>|Mi<U+0161>kulin|2010|p=486}}</ref> A substantial proportion of the refugees were settled in [[Baranja]], in houses owned by [[Croat]]s displaced from the region.<ref>{{harvnb|Ba<U+0161>i<U+0107>|Mi<U+0161>kulin|2010|pp=491<U+2013>492}}</ref> Based on the reports of the fleeing civilians, [[SFR Yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] government accused Croatia of [[ethnic cleansing]] and other [[civil rights]] violations. Deputy prime minister Aleksandar Mitrovi<U+0107> wrote to the [[European Community Monitor Mission]] (ECMM), accusing Croatia of causing numerous casualties, devastation and displacement of Serb civilians. Even though the accusations were contrasted by evacuation plans put together by SAO Western Slavonia authorities on 25 October,<ref>{{harvnb|Ba<U+0161>i<U+0107>|Mi<U+0161>kulin|2010|p=487}}</ref> and by testimony of civilians who remained in the area and claimed that the TO called the population to flee claiming "[[Usta<U+0161>e]] are coming [...] killing every Serb",<ref>{{harvnb|Ba<U+0161>i<U+0107>|Mi<U+0161>kulin|2010|p=488}}</ref> media in Serbia widely [[Role of the media in the Yugoslav wars|reported on alleged atrocities]]. The reports related the Croatian offensive to [[World War II]] and [[List of massacres in the Independent State of Croatia|massacres committed by the Independent State of Croatia]] in that period.<ref>{{harvnb|Ba<U+0161>i<U+0107>|Mi<U+0161>kulin|2010|p=489}}</ref> On 3 November, the [[Presidency of Yugoslavia]] condemned the offensive citing destruction of 18 Serb villages, and the next day the [[National Assembly (Serbia)|National Assembly]] of Serbia appealed to the international community for help.<ref>{{harvnb|Ba<U+0161>i<U+0107>|Mi<U+0161>kulin|2010|pp=489<U+2013>490}}</ref>

In response to the situation and a request received from the Presidency of Yugoslavia, an ECMM team toured the area affected by the offensive on 6 November, targeting those locations where the media reports indicated the atrocities occurred, including Velika Peratovica, Mala Peratovica, Gornja Ra<U+0161>enica, Donja Ra<U+0161>enica and Lon<U+010D>arica. The ECMM report of 6 November refuted the accusations. The ECMM team found only one Serb couple remaining in the area, but they denied claims that the HV mistreated the civilians left behind. The ECMM team reported that there was no systematic destruction of houses, even though a number of structures exhibited artillery bombardment damage and a small number of houses, farms and [[haystack]]s were recently torched. However, the report states that the team was unable to determine if the HV was to blame, or if the villagers took revenge against SAO Western Krajina leaders, or if the destruction was a result of a [[scorched earth]] policy applied by the retreating force.<ref>{{harvnb|Ba<U+0161>i<U+0107>|Mi<U+0161>kulin|2010|p=490}}</ref>

The HV offensives in western Slavonia conducted in late 1991&mdash;Operations Hurricane-10, Swath-10, and Papuk-91&mdash;created a total of 20,000 Serb refugees. They fled from the area when the JNA ordered the Croatian Serb forces to withdraw,<ref>{{harvnb|HRW|13 February 1992|loc=note 28}}</ref> and were subsequently settled in JNA-held Baranja region in the east of Croatia.<ref>{{harvnb|HRW|21 January 1992|p=297}}</ref>

===Ceasefire===
{{main|Vance plan}}
A ceasefire of 3 January 1992 allowed implementation of the [[Vance plan]], which provided for protection of civilians in specific areas designated as [[United Nations Protected Area (UNPROFOR)|UN Protected Areas]] (UNPAs) and deployment of UN peacekeepers in Croatia.<ref>{{harvnb|Armatta|2010|pp=194<U+2013>196}}</ref> One of the UNPAs defined by the plan, UNPA Western Slavonia, encompassed parts of municipalities of Novska and Nova Gradi<U+0161>ka, as well as entire municipalities of Daruvar, Grubi<U+0161>no Polje and Pakrac. Thus the UNPA covered the area held by the JNA on 3 January, additional territory to the north, recaptured by the HV in late 1991, and towns which never came under SAO Western Slavonia control&mdash;such as Grubi<U+0161>no Polje and Daruvar.<ref>{{harvnb|Ramcharan|1997|pp=449<U+2013>450}}</ref> The peacekeeping force named [[United Nations Protection Force]] (UNPROFOR), initially expected to be 10,000-strong,<ref>{{harvnb|CIA|2002|p=106}}</ref> started to deploy on 8 March.<ref>{{harvnb|Trbovich|2008|p=300}}</ref>

